	//    Let S' = {nums[i]/p | nums[i] in S}. We need gcd(S') = 1.

	// Condition |S| < n is the only constraint on size.

	// If there is at least one element nums[i] such that nums[i] % p != 0,
	// then any subsequence containing nums[i] cannot have a GCD of p (or any multiple of p).
	// Therefore, any "good subsequence" must only consist of elements divisible by p.

	// Let's consider only the elements divisible by p. Let this subset be N_p.
	// If N_p is empty, no good subsequence exists.
	// If |N_p| = 1, say N_p = {x}, then any subsequence S from N_p has |S|=1 and gcd(S)=x/p * p = x.
	// If x/p = 1, then gcd(S)=p. But if |N_p|=1, then |S|=1, and since n >= 2, |S| < n is satisfied.
	// However, if |N_p|=1, the only non-empty subsequence is {x}, and its length is 1.
	// The problem states the subsequence must have length STRICTLY LESS than n.
	// If N_p = {x}, and n > 1, then |S|=1 < n is true. So if gcd(x)=p, it's a good subsequence.

	// Case 1: A single element subsequence S = {nums[i]} is a good subsequence.
	// This requires:
	// 1. nums[i] % p == 0
	// 2. nums[i] / p == 1  => nums[i] == p
	// 3. |S| = 1 < n. Since n >= 2, this is always true.

	// Case 2: A multi-element subsequence S = {nums[i1], ..., nums[ik]} (k >= 2) is a good subsequence.
	// This requires:
	// 1. All nums[ij] % p == 0.
	// 2. gcd({nums[i1]/p, ..., nums[ik]/p}) = 1.
	// 3. k < n. Since we are looking for existence, we just need to check if *any* such set exists.

